author: Tim Emiola
commit_message:
Replace explicit type hints with py2.7 compatible type comments

N.B. An alternative approach is to put the type declarations into stub (.pyi)
files.  Rather than do that this commit uses type comments
<http://tinyurl.com/k944sug> for the following reasons:

- the type declarations are closer to the functions they annotate, so
  maintaining them is easier

- type declarations are declared consistently for inner functions. There does
  not appear to be a way to declare types in separate stub files for inner
  functions, so it's necessary to use type comments for those.

- fewer additional maintenance tasks, .e.g, no need be concerned about packaging
  the packaging .pyi files correctly, no need to maintain .pyi files for test
  files

author: Tim Emiola
commit_message:
Move the vendored typing module into a vendor package

- makes a new package, vendor.python3 and moves typing.py into it

This is a bit neater, and helps resolve the import of the typing module in
_compat.py correctly in python2.7.

I.e, in python2.7, the lines

  from typing import *
  from typing import _Union

imports from the typing module in the same package, rather than
choosing the top-level typing module.  By making any such imports from
a vendor subpackage, we avoid this issue.

author: Tim Emiola
commit_message:
Vendor python2.7 typing.py

This ensures that all the latest features of typing.py (available in python 3.6)
are available; and allows the application of a small patch that fixes a major
issue.

Small Patch
-----------

The patch is on line #1223, where __subclasscheck__ is only permitted for
generic types from two modules, abc and functools.
```
    if sys._getframe(1).f_globals['__name__'] not in ['abc', 'functools']:
       ...
```

To support python2.7, we need to add 'singledispatch' to the list of permitted
modules, as singledispatch is packaged in it's own file singledispatch.py rather
than functools.py as it is in python3
```
    if sys._getframe(1).f_globals['__name__'] not in ['abc', 'functools',
                                                      'singledispatch']:
       ...
```

author: Tim Emiola
commit_message:
Fix outstanding things broken on python 2.7

I.e, with these additional changes, all unittests pass on 2.7.13

Most of the edits are minor tweaks to related to obvious differences between
python2 and python3. E.g

- maximum value of int in hypothesis tests
- checking against the str value of something in unittests

There is one real change:  Converter is modified to simplify howt
the unstruct_strat attributes is used.  The prior behaviour
where the property setter is invoked on __init__ did not work on python 2.7.13

To correct this, the behaviour of this attribute is modified a little:

- the value of the unstrut_strat attribute is now simply a value of the
  UnstructureStrategy enum, and all references to it in cattr package have
  been updated to reflect this

- unstructure_attrs is now a declared method that switches on the value of the
  unstruct_strat attribute

Remove ability to set unstruct_strat dynamically after creation

and better avoided.

author: Ran Benita
commit_message:
Remove ability to set {un,}structure_attrs dynamically after creation

Currently, these two fields are not marked an private, and in the case
of `structure_attrs`, also documented.

Remove this ability, for these reasons:

- There are two alternatives:

    1. Create a new Converter, passing the desired strategy in the
       constructor.

    2. Use the explicit astuple/fromtuple/asdict/fromdict functions,
       instead of relying on the default.

- Changing the strategy after creation can wreak some havoc, e.g.
  someone might change the global Converter to use tuples, which would
  break any library which uses e.g. cattrs.structure expecting it to use
  dicts.

- It hampers some optimizations - since the strategy can change, some
  indirection is required which adds overhead.

- (Not sure if this is a problem) If a user changes only one of
  `structure_attrs`/`unstructure_attrs`, then `structure` and
  `unstructure` are not using the same strategy.

BREAKING CHANGE: Removes documented functionality.

author: Joel Dodge
commit_message:
Fix test_unmodified_generated_unstructuring test

This was broken for 3.7 due to how `cattr.generation.make_dict_unstructure_fn`
reaches directly into `converter._unstructure_func.dispatch` to get the
converter function passing the annotated type of the field. In 3.7 the
`TypeError: Subscripted generics cannot be used with class and instance checks`
issue causes the `dispatch` to be the fallback identity converter func.

Normal usage (i.e. unstructure_attrs_asdict) passes in field_inst.__class__
which would never hit the above `TypeError` so this issue is unique to
`make_dict_unstructure_fn`

author: Peter Gaultney
commit_message:
fix MultiStrategyDispatch to work with new GenConverter and attrs inheritance

Because the GenConverter specifically handles generating code for
attrs classes, and because it registers hooks that don't require
function dispatch, singledispatch was preventing subclasses from
having code generated for them, because they would trigger the
previously-generated base class's structure/unstructure code.

This changes MultiStrategyDispatch to allow for a class-based hook to
specifically avoid single-dispatch. Since we know that a given attrs
class can always have code generated for it, we don't really want to
share dispatch across subclasses - like the original Converter, we
want to make sure we're structuring each individual attrs class as its
own separate type.

author: Fabian Raab
commit_message:
Fix  __parameters__ access in gen._generate_mapping

There are Generic types in the typing modules
from which you can inherit in your own classes
which do not have an __parameters__ attribute,
such classes are now ignored making
gen._generate_mapping effectively a no-op
in case the class do not have an __parameters__
attribute.

As https://github.com/ilevkivskyi/typing_inspect/blob/8f6aa2075ba448ab322def454137e7c59b9b302d/typing_inspect.py#L405
is showing there are also cases where __parameters__
could be None, so I test for both cases, that it
is None or that it does not exist.

See Also:
https://github.com/python-attrs/cattrs/issues/217

author: Zixuan Li
commit_message:
Make validation notes picklable. (#408)

Certain test runners pickle the exceptions raised to accumulate them from
multiple processes.

For exceptions with `AttributeValidationNote` and/or `IterableValidationNote`
attached, because we have overridden `__new__` on these classes, pickle cannot
correctly unpickle them with the required arguments. For this use case,
exceptions being picklable is necessary to accumulate errors with the
`multiprocessing` setup.

This implements `__getnewargs__` to fix this problem.

Certain test runners that pickle the exceptions raised to accumulate
them from multiple processes. For exceptions with `AttributeValidationNote`
and/or `IterableValidationNote`, because we have overriden __new__ on
these classes, pickle is not able to correctly unpickle them with the required
arguments. This implements __getnewargs__ to fix this problem.

Signed-off-by: Zixuan James Li <p359101898@gmail.com>
